TAURI THERMAE, line 249, called Aquae Tauri or Taurianae, by S. Gregorius, Dialog. 4, 55, was in Etruria, three miles north of Civita Vecehia, at the foot of the volcanic mountains of La Tolfa, and is now called Bagni di Ferrata. Pliny, Nat. Hist. 3, 5, 8, refers to the inhabitants of this place as Aquenses cognomine Taurino-3. The waters, whose freedom from an offensive odour and whose delicate flavour the poet refers t0, are still used both for drinking and for bathing.
